## Here's a basic Dockerfile that sets up a PySpark environment with Delta:

# Use base image with pre-installed Spark and PySpark
FROM jupyter/pyspark-notebook

# Set environment variables for Spark
ENV SPARK_MASTER_PORT 7077
ENV SPARK_MASTER_WEBUI_PORT 8080

# Install Delta dependencies
RUN conda install -y pandas==1.0.3 \
    && conda install -y pyarrow==0.17.0 \
    && conda install -y snappy==1.1.7

# Copy local delta files to Docker image
COPY delta-core_2.12-0.7.0.jar /usr/local/spark/jars/delta-core_2.12-0.7.0.jar

# Launch Spark Master and Workers
CMD /usr/local/spark/sbin/start-master.sh \
    && /usr/local/spark/sbin/start-worker.sh spark://spark-master:7077



### Here is an example of a Docker Compose file that sets up a PySpark environment with Delta support:

version: '3'
services:
  master:
    image: spark-base
    environment:
      SPARK_ROLE: master
      SPARK_MASTER_HOST: master
    ports:
      - "8080:8080"
      - "7077:7077"
  worker1:
    image: spark-base
    environment:
      SPARK_ROLE: worker
      SPARK_MASTER_HOST: master
  worker2:
    image: spark-base
    environment:
      SPARK_ROLE: worker
      SPARK_MASTER_HOST: master


#In this example, we are using the gettyimages/spark Docker image version 2.4.5 with Hadoop 2.7. We have one Spark master node and two Spark worker nodes. Each node is defined as a separate service in the Docker Compose file. The environment variables are used to configure the Spark worker nodes, such as specifying the number of cores, memory, and port numbers. The ports are also exposed to allow access to the Spark web UI. The Spark worker nodes depend on the Spark master node, so that they can connect to it.



### WITH Minio server


version: '3'
services:
  master:
    image: spark
    command: /spark/sbin/start-master.sh
    ports:
      - "7077:7077"
    environment:
      SPARK_WORKER_CORES: 2
      SPARK_WORKER_MEMORY: 2g
      SPARK_WORKER_INSTANCES: 2
      SPARK_WORKER_WEBUI_PORT: 8080

  worker1:
    image: spark
    command: /spark/sbin/start-worker.sh spark://master:7077
    depends_on:
      - master

  worker2:
    image: spark
    command: /spark/sbin/start-worker.sh spark://master:7077
    depends_on:
      - master

  mini-server:
    image: minio/minio
    command: server /data
    ports:
      - "9000:9000"
    environment:
      MINIO_ACCESS_KEY: myaccesskey
      MINIO_SECRET_KEY: mysecretkey
    volumes:
      - data:/data

volumes:
  data:
    external: true
    driver: local
    name: data
    driver_opts:
      type: none
      o: bind
      device: /home/data



# In this file, the master and worker1 and worker2 nodes use the official Spark image and start the Spark master and worker processes, respectively. The mini-server node uses the Minio image and starts a mini S3-compatible server. The volumes section maps a local directory to the Minio container's data volume, which Minio will use to store the objects.

# The environment section of the master service sets some Spark configuration options, such as the number of cores and memory to use for each worker, and the number of worker instances to run. The Spark master and worker nodes communicate with each other using the default 7077 port, which is exposed as a host port in the ports section.

#Finally, the mini-server node exposes its default 9000 port, which Spark can use to connect to the mini-server and access the S3 storage. To connect Spark to the mini-server, you will need to set the spark.hadoop.fs.s3a.endpoint and spark.hadoop.fs.s3a.access.key and spark.hadoop.fs.s3a.secret.key configuration options to the appropriate values in your Spark code or configuration file.

# The "data" field under the "volumes" section in the Dockerfile refers to a named data volume that is created for persistent storage. This volume allows the data to persist even if the container is deleted, recreated, or moved to another host. The "data" volume maps a host directory to a directory in the container file system, and it can be used to store data that needs to persist even when the container is recreated.

# In this case, the purpose of the "data" volume is to store data that is used by the Spark and Delta services, and to persist it even if the container is recreated. By mapping a host directory to the named data volume, it is possible to store the data on a host file system, which provides a higher level of durability and performance compared to storing the data within the container file system.